  "prompt": "How do say \"I love you\" in Spanish?",
  "response": "In Spanish, there are a couple of common ways to say \"I love you,\" each with its own nuance:\n\n1. **\"Te quiero\"**  \n   - **Usage**: This phrase is widely used to express love and affection. It's appropriate for romantic relationships but also commonly used among family members and close friends.\n   - **Nuance**: While it translates to \"I love you,\" it can carry a slightly lighter or more casual tone compared to \"Te amo.\"\n\n2. **\"Te amo\"**  \n   - **Usage**: This is a more intense and profound expression of love, typically reserved for deep romantic relationships.\n   - **Nuance**: It conveys a stronger, more passionate love and is often used in serious or long-term relationships.\n\n**Example Sentences:**\n- *Te quiero mucho.*  \n  (\"I love you very much.\")\n  \n- *Te amo con todo mi coraz\u00f3n.*  \n  (\"I love you with all my heart.\")\n\n**Pronunciation Tips:**\n- *Te quiero* is pronounced as \"teh kee-EHR-oh.\"\n- *Te amo* is pronounced as \"teh AH-mo.\"\n\n**Cultural Note:**  \nThe choice between \"Te quiero\" and \"Te amo\" can depend on personal preference and regional usage. In some Spanish-speaking countries, one may be favored over the other in certain contexts.\n\nChoose the expression that best fits the depth and context of your relationship.",
